<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-285-214  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 285 214.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Digital Review  May 22 1989 v6 n20 p22(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>System helps users create, update manuals. (Data Retrieval Corp'sOn-Line TextBook Manuals) (product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Grygo, Gene.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Data retrieval Corp's On-Line TextBook Manuals software packageaids in the creation and updating of safety procedure manuals fromthe company's TextDBMS centralized database.andP;  The system providesfull search and retrieval and a table of contents andautomatically creates an index of key words.andP;  Graphic images canbe scanned from any microcomputer-based CAD-CAM package and can beused to accompany text.andP;  The program provides remote access toheadquarters from district sales offices.andP;  A Unix version is underdevelopment.andP;  The price of packages for one to 20 users starts at$14,925 and the price for 20 or more users is $18,450.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Data Retrieval Corp. (product introduction).andO;Product:   On-Line TextBook Manuals (Data base management system) (productintroduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionData Base Management SystemsTechnical WritingDocumentationReference Books.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>System Helps Users Create, Update ManualsandM;MILWAUKEE -- Data Retrieval has introduced a database application that isdesigned to help technical writers and end users manage reference materialssuch as manuals and price catalogs.andM;The On-Line TextBook Manuals product allows users to create and update safetyprocedure manuals from TextDBMS, Data Retrieval's centralized database, saidThomas Erickson, Data Retrieval's vice president of development.andM;The system provides full search and retrieval, a table of contents and anautomatically created index of key words, which users can change.andP;  Thosechanges can occur while someone is still reading a page, Erickson said.andM;&quot;We're actually assuming that this is going to be used by those who arealready creating manuals,&quot; Erickson said.andM;In another, higher-priced version of the product, graphics can be created toaccompany text, according to Erickson.andP;  &quot;We see the addition of graphics asvery critical,&quot; he said.andM;Graphics images created by any PC-based CAD/CAM package can be scanned andstored for later use, Erickson said.andM;The insurance and manufacturing industries are showing the greatest interestin this product, according to Erickson.andP;  &quot;[But] this application is turningout to have appeal across industries,&quot; he said.andM;Users at a terminal can browse through Data Retrieval's TextDBMS database andinvoke a command to fetch the appropriate manual, Erickson said.andM;&quot;The idea is that the average end user can use the system with no training,&quot;he said.andP;  For example, an insurance salesperson can access the system findthe proper manual and print out only those sections needed, Ericksonexplained.andM;Printing of an entire document is possible, he said.andP;  &quot;[But] that kind ofgoes counter to putting it on-line,&quot; he said.andM;Remote access from a district sales office to headquarters is also a keyfeature of this product, Erickson said.andP;  &quot;It's easier to maintain a manual ina central location,&quot; he said.andM;A Unix version of the product is in the works, company officials said.andP;  Also,future updates of the product should be compatible with other TextDBMS-basedapplications under development.andM;The prices for On-Line TextBook Manuals differ according to graphics andnon-graphics capabilities.andP;  A non-graphics package for one to 20 users sellsfor $9,300.andP;  For 20 or more users, the price is $12,375.andM;Prices of packages for one to 20 users that include graphics capabilitiesstart at $14,925.andP;  The price for 20 or more users is $18,450.andM;For additional information, Data Retrieval Corp. can be contacted at 8889 N.andO;Deerwood Drive, Milwaukee, WI 53223, (414) 355-5900.andO;</TEXT></DOC>